# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1987-cricket-world-cup-final
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] The **1975 Cricket World Cup Final** was a One Day International cricket match played at Lord's, London, on 21 June 1975 to determine the winner of the 1975 Cricket World Cup.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] It was the second time that the West Indies and Australia had met in the tournament, after playing against each other in the group stage.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] The West Indies won the match by 17 runs to claim their first title.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] West Indies qualified for the knockouts with a first-place finish in Group B.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] The team won all three of their matches against Australia, Pakistan and Sri Lanka.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] Then in the semi-final against New Zealand, the opposition opened brilliantly, but when Glenn Turner fell, the wickets tumbled the West Indies scored the required 158 to reach the final.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] Australia made it through to the knockouts in second place with their only loss being against the West Indies.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] But they did defeat Pakistan and Sri Lanka to take on England in the semi-final.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] Gary Gilmour took six wickets in the English innings to help them through to the final.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] The first final was played on 21 June (Midsummer of that year), a sunny day, in front of a capacity crowd of 26,765.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] Australia won the toss and invited the West Indies to bat, hoping to make use of ideal bowling conditions.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] The first moment of drama came when opener Roy Fredericks was dismissed hit wicket; he hooked a bouncer from Dennis Lillee for six, but in his follow-through lost his balance and knocked the bails off the stumps.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] Australia were on top at 50/3 when West Indian captain Clive Lloyd came to the crease in partnership with veteran Rohan Kanhai.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] The pair swung the match in the West Indies' favour by putting on 149 for the fourth wicket.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] Kanhai played the anchor role – not scoring for 11 overs – while Lloyd took on the Australian bowling attack, surviving a dropped catch on 26 to score a century off 82 balls with 12 fours and two sixes, being dismissed shortly afterwards for 102.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] Kanhai, in what would be his farewell from international cricket, scored an invaluable 55.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] Solid contributions from Keith Boyce and Bernard Julien helped the West Indies close their innings at 291/8.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] Burly left-arm seamer Gary Gilmour was the pick of the Australian bowlers with 5/48, backing up his strong semi-final performance.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] The Australian run chase began steadily: at the 20-over mark, they were 80/1 with Alan Turner and captain Ian Chappell taking advantage of an easy pitch and fast outfield.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] Then Viv Richards, who had failed with the bat, left his mark on the match with the next three run-outs.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] First he swooped in and dismissed Turner with a direct hit from close range, then Greg Chappell was also out with a direct hit after a slight misfield.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] Doug Walters came in and helped his captain steady the ship.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] Australia were at 162/3 with 21 overs remaining when Chappell, facing his opposing captain, pushed a ball to the left of mid-wicket and started off for a run.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] He hesitated initially when he saw Richards approaching but started off again after Richards fumbled the ball, only to be caught short of the crease by Richards' lightning recovery and return to Lloyd at the bowler's end.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] In each situation, the batsmen probably would have made the run had they not hesitated.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] When Lillee joined Jeff Thomson as last man in, Australia required 59 runs to win off seven overs.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] The duo kept the game alive, putting on an unlikely last-wicket stand.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] With three overs remaining Lillee hit a no-ball to Fredericks at extra cover off Vanburn Holder and the crowd rushed on to the field oblivious to the umpire's call.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] Amid the chaos, Fredericks attempted a run-out but missed and the ball disappeared into the crowd.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] Lillee and Thomson kept running between the wickets until the crowd was dispersed.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] When play was resumed, the umpires decided to give Australia two runs.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] After protest from Thomson, they awarded three runs.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] The match finally ended three balls later after Thomson had run a leg bye and Lillee scored a single.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] The final wicket fell with Thomson swinging wildly and missing.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] Having not realised the wicket-keeper had held the ball Thomson set off for a run, attempted to return after recognising his mistake but not before Murray knocked the bails off with a well-aimed underarm throw with his gloves on for a run-out.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] The game ended at 8:43 pm after nearly 10 hours play.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] Another pitch invasion ensued as the players and umpires ran for safety, with Thomson having his cricket pads stolen, Boyce losing his shoes and umpire Bird having his hat taken.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] Bird later said that he came across the stolen hat being worn by a bus conductor in London a year after the event.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] When he asked about it, he was told by the conductor, who did not recognise Bird, that he'd "won the race" by sprinting onto the field at the final to take it.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup-squads] This is a list of cricket squads that were selected for the 1975 Cricket World Cup which took place in England between 7 and 21 June 1975.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup-squads] The eight teams competing in the competition were restricted to selecting a 14-member squad before the tournament began.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] The **1975 Cricket World Cup** (officially called the **Prudential Cup '75**) was the inaugural men's Cricket World Cup, and the first major tournament in the history of One Day International (ODI) cricket.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] Organised by the International Cricket Conference (ICC), it took place in England, between 7 June and 21 June 1975.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] The tournament was sponsored by Prudential Assurance Company and had eight participating countries: the six Test-playing teams of the time – Australia, England, India, New Zealand, Pakistan, the West Indies – and the two leading Associate nations at the time – Sri Lanka and East Africa.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] The teams were divided into two groups of four, with each team playing each other in their group once; the top two from each group qualified for the semi-finals, with the winners of these matches meeting in the final.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] Each match consisted of 60 overs per side and was played in traditional white clothing and with red balls; all were played and ended in daylight.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] England and New Zealand finished as the top two teams in Group A, while the West Indies finished top of the Group B table ahead of Australia as the four teams qualified through to the semi-finals.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] After Australia defeated England and the West Indies defeated New Zealand in the semi-finals, the West Indies which came into the tournament as favourites, defeated Australia in the final at Lord's by 17 runs to become the first World Cup winners.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] New Zealand batsman, Glenn Turner was the top run-scorer for the tournament with 333 runs, whilst Australian bowler Gary Gilmour was the top wicket-taker with 11 wickets despite only playing in the final two matches.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] The first multilateral cricket competition at international level was the 1912 Triangular Tournament in England.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] This was played between the three test nations at the time – England, Australia and South Africa.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] The concept was later dropped because of inclement weather and a lack of public interest.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] The first one-day match to occur was in 1962 when four English county cricket teams filled in a gap to play in a limited overs knockout competition.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] It was won by Northamptonshire who defeated Leicestershire by five wickets.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] The limited-over format had been used in what sponsors marketed as a 'World Cricket Cup' in England in 1966 and 1967, contested between England, a Rest of the World XI, and a touring team (the West Indies in 1966 and Pakistan in 1967).
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] The marketing of the event was clearly influenced by the hosting of the 1966 FIFA World Cup in the same country.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] The 1966 'World Cricket Cup' was won by England, that in 1967 by the Rest of the World.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] A report in the *Cricketer* implied that the last such match in this "Triangular Tournament", between Pakistan and the Rest of the World was neither well-attended nor taken entirely seriously: "It was a pity that a larger crowd was not present ...
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] Sobers took the Cup and the World Xl took the gold medals.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] It was not until 1971 that the first official One Day International (ODI) took place at the Melbourne Cricket Ground (MCG) as a replacement for the third test of the 1970–71 Ashes series between Australia and England.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] This was due to a deluge of rain that had affected the match for the first three days of the test.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] The match was a forty over match with each over being eight deliveries.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] After England made 190 from 39.4 overs, Australia chased the target at a steady rate to secure the match with 42 balls remaining.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] Two years later at Lord's during the 1973 Women's Cricket World Cup, plans were made for a men's tournament to take place in 1975.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] The tournament was planned to involve all the Test nations at the time in two group stages with the top two in each group qualifying for the knockout stage with the final at Lord's.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] The format of the 1975 Cricket World Cup had the eight teams split into two groups of four, with each team playing the others in their group once.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] Each match was played over 60 overs per side with group stage matches scheduled to take place between 7 and 14 June.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] Each match was played entirely during day, with a cut off time of 7.30 pm.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] Three days were allocated to each match with each able to be continued if they were halted for rain or bad light.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] The top two teams from each group advanced to the semi-finals on 18 June, with the winners qualifying for the final at Lord's on 21 June.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] Eight teams were invited to compete at the World Cup: the six full members of the International Cricket Conference (ICC), and two other teams – Sri Lanka and East Africa.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] South Africa was not allowed to complete due to the sporting boycott of the country which took place during apartheid era, the ICC having placed a moratorium on tours of the country in 1970.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] Before the competition began the teams were split into two groups.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] The ICC made the decision to place the two teams which were not Test playing countries in separate groups.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] They also decided to place England and Australia in separate groups and to do the same with India and Pakistan.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] Six grounds were used to host matches during the tournament.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] The announcement of venues began on 26 July 1973 when the ICC announced that the tournament would be played, with Lord's as the venue for the final.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] The remaining venues were announced on 5 November 1974, with the scheduling for the tournament announced alongside that for the five county cricket tournaments that would take place during the 1975 season.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] Other than Lord's, which hosted only one group stage match, and The Oval which hosted three, each of the grounds was used for two matches during the group stage.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] Headingley and The Oval were the grounds chosen for the two semi-finals.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] Before the competition began each team named a squad of 14 players.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] Heading into the first Cricket World Cup, the Ladbrokes betting agency had the West Indies as the favourites at 9–4.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] This was followed by England at 11–4 with Pakistan and Australia in third and fourth respectively.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] East Africa was last in the betting odds at 1500–1.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] Before the tournament, most of the teams played in warm-up matches against English county teams to get used to the English conditions with most of the national teams getting wins.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] Only East Africa, Sri Lanka and India lost at least one warm-up match before the tournament.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] Australia played in Canada, losing to Eastern Canada and drawing with Toronto, before heading to England.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] Eight days before the World Cup, the ICC declared in a unanimous decision that any of the balls that went over a batsman's head would be called wide due to the fast short-pitched bowling.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] The opening round of matches took place on 7 June with four matches being played.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] The match at Lord's saw England deliver the highest score by a team in the 60 over match with 334 runs being scored.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] Dennis Amiss top scored for the English with 137 from 147 balls helped by Keith Fletcher and Chris Old who each recorded a half-century.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] In response, Sunil Gavaskar batted through the entire innings for only 36 runs off 174 balls, prompting Gulabrai Ramchand to speculate that he was treating the match as batting practice.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] Australia opened their campaign with a win against Pakistan at Headingley with a 73-run victory.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] This was due to Dennis Lillee's five-wicket haul which brought Pakistan's hope of a win crashing down as they collapsed from 181 for four to be all out for 205.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] Earlier, Ross Edwards top scored for Australia with 80 as he aided the Australians in getting 94 runs from the last 13 overs to bring Australia to 278 for seven from their 60 overs.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] The other two matches saw easy wins for the West Indies and New Zealand.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] For Glenn Turner, he occupied the crease during the whole New Zealand innings as he top scored with 171 as New Zealand won by 181 runs over East Africa.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] The West Indies took a nine-wicket victory over Sri Lanka who became the first team to score under 100 runs in a One Day International.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] Despite missing two players due to operation – Asif Iqbal – and examinations – Imran Khan – Pakistan was not fazed by the missing players in the second round of games with the team scoring 266 for seven from their 60 overs with standing captain Majid Khan top scoring for Pakistan with 60.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] In response, the West Indies fell to 166 for eight which included a period of three wickets for only 10 runs as Bernard Julien, Clive Lloyd and Keith Boyce all losing their wickets.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] But the last wicket pair of Deryck Murray and Andy Roberts stole the match away as the West Indies won by a wicket off the final over.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] On the field, Alan Turner scored a century as Australia ended with 328 with Sri Lanka falling 52 runs short as John Mason from *The Daily Telegraph* stated that they might not have many new admirers with their short ball stuff sending two Sri Lankan batsman to hospital.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] Group A saw two convincing wins to England and India.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] At Trent Bridge, Keith Fletcher top scored for England with 131 as he guided the English to their second victory and going to the lead of the group table with an 80-run win over New Zealand.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] The other match in Group A saw 720 spectators observe India record a 10-wicket victory with Madan Lal taking three wickets for India, after East Africa were all-out for only 120.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] With the match sold out four days in advance, the West Indies took on Australia to see who would finish top of Group B.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] With the ball swinging in the air, the pair of Rod Marsh and Ross Edwards guided Australia to 192 with a 99-run partnership for the sixth wicket after Australia fell to 61/5.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] In response, the West Indies went on to take a seven-wicket victory with Alvin Kallicharran top scoring with 78, which included a period of 31 runs of nine Dennis Lillee deliveries as the West Indies finished top of Group B.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] Pakistan ended their tournament with a 192-run victory over Sri Lanka at Trent Bridge with half centuries to Zaheer Abbas, Majid Khan and Sadiq Mohammad.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] In Group A, New Zealand sealed their spot in the semi-finals with a four-wicket victory over India off the back of a century from Glenn Turner as he hit twelve fours on his way to an unbeaten innings of 114.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] Only Ramesh Sethi offered much resistance, lasting for 32 overs to score 30.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] The knockout stage of the Cricket World Cup consisted of two single-elimination rounds leading to a final.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] If the match was delayed due to rain there were two reserve days to play out the match.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] The first semi-final was between England and Australia at Headingley.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] For Australia, their one change in bringing in Gary Gilmour for Ashley Mallett proved critical in booking Australia's spot into the final.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] This was due to the grassy pitch that both captains would criticise after the match.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] After Australia elected to field first, Gilmour took six wickets for 14 runs as he had England at 37 for seven after he bowled his 12 overs.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] Mike Denness attempted to bring England back but would lose his wicket as England fell for 93.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] In the run-chase, Australia collapsed to 39 for six before Gilmour partnered with Doug Walters as they chased the remaining runs to earn Australia a berth in the final.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] The second semi-final was between the West Indies and New Zealand at The Oval.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] Batting first, New Zealand reached 92 for only one loss at the lunch break.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] After lunch though, they collapsed to 158 with Geoff Howarth top scoring for New Zealand with 51, while Bernard Julien was the top wicket taker with four wickets.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] The final match on 21 June was sold out three days beforehand.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] With the West Indies being favourites for the match, they were asked by Ian Chappell to bat first and would go on to score 291 for eight wickets from 60 overs.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] After being given a second chance from a Ross Edwards dropped chance at mid-wicket, Clive Lloyd went on to top score for the West Indies with 102.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] Gary Gilmour was the best of the Australian bowlers with five wickets for 48 runs.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] In response, Ian Chappell scored a half-century to set up the foundation for Australia before three run-outs from the hands of Viv Richards put the pressure on Australia as they collapsed to 233 for nine.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] A final-wicket partnership of 41 from Dennis Lillee and Jeff Thomson brought Australia within 18 runs of victory.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] But a fifth run-out of the innings saw Australia bowled out for 274 and would see the West Indies win by 17 runs, claiming the first men's World Cup.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] Glenn Turner of New Zealand ended the tournament as the leading run scorer for the 1975 edition with his 333 runs coming in four games which included an unbeaten 171 against East Africa, which was also the highest score of the tournament.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] In second place was English player Dennis Amiss with Pakistan's Majid Khan rounding out the top three.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] Australian player Gary Gilmour was the tournament's leading wicket taker with 11 wickets from his two games, which included the best tournament figures in the semi-finals when he took six wickets for 14 against England.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1975-cricket-world-cup] Bernard Julien and Keith Boyce (both from the West Indies) finished in second place, both getting 10 wickets for the tournament.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-cricket-world-cup-final] The final of the 1979 ICC Cricket World Cup was played in Lord's, London on 23 June.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-cricket-world-cup-final] This was the second time that Lord's had hosted an ICC Cricket World Cup final.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-cricket-world-cup-final] The match was won by the West Indies when they defeated England by 92 runs to lift the trophy.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-cricket-world-cup-final] The match was the second consecutive World Cup final hosted at Lord's, following the inaugural 1975 final.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-cricket-world-cup-final] West Indies reached a second consecutive final after defeating Pakistan by 43 runs in the semi-final.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-cricket-world-cup-final] Previously, they had won the 1975 final.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-cricket-world-cup-final] England was making their first appearance at a World Cup final after defeating New Zealand by 9 runs in the semi-finals.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-cricket-world-cup-final] This was also the first appearance by a European nation at a World Cup final.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-cricket-world-cup-final] Bob Willis, England's leading bowler, missed the final after being injured in the semi-final.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-cricket-world-cup-final] England won the toss and chose to field first.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-cricket-world-cup-final] The West Indies got off to a bad start, falling to 99/4 with the loss of Greenidge, Haynes, Kallicharan, and captain Clive Lloyd.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-cricket-world-cup-final] However, Vivian Richards (138 from 157 balls, 11 fours, 3 sixes) and Collis King (86 from 66 balls, 10 fours, 3 sixes) consolidated the innings.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-cricket-world-cup-final] King especially ripped through the English bowling, with a strike rate of 130.3.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-cricket-world-cup-final] The West Indies were already at 5/238 when the 139 run partnership ended with the loss of Collis King.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-cricket-world-cup-final] Vivian Richards and the tail then took the West Indies to a very imposing total of 286 (9 wickets, 60 overs).
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-cricket-world-cup-final] The English batsmen got off to a good start.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-cricket-world-cup-final] But the openers, Mike Brearley (64 from 130 balls, 7 fours) and Geoff Boycott (57 from 105 balls, 3 fours) scored very slowly.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-cricket-world-cup-final] They put together a very methodical opening partnership of 129 runs in 38 overs, playing as if the match were a five-day Test.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-cricket-world-cup-final] By the time both batsmen were out, the run rate had risen too high.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-cricket-world-cup-final] Graham Gooch played some hefty strokes in scoring his 32, taking England to 183/2.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-cricket-world-cup-final] However, the loss of Derek Randall triggered the most devastating collapse in World Cup history, as England lost 8 wickets for 11 runs.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-cricket-world-cup-final] They were eventually all out for 194 in 51 overs.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-cricket-world-cup-final] Vivian Richards was declared Man of the Match.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-cricket-world-cup] The **1979 Cricket World Cup** (officially called the **Prudential Cup '79**) was the second edition of the Cricket World Cup.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-cricket-world-cup] Organised by the International Cricket Conference, it was held in England from 9 to 23 June 1979.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-cricket-world-cup] The tournament was once again sponsored by the Prudential Assurance Company and had eight teams participating in the tournament with the only change being Canada who qualified with Sri Lanka in the qualifier for the tournament.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-cricket-world-cup] The format remained the same with two teams qualifying from each group with the final once again being at Lord's.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-cricket-world-cup] England joined first-time semi-finalists Pakistan as the qualifiers from Group A, while the West Indies finished top of Group B ahead of New Zealand.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-cricket-world-cup] After the West Indies and England both won their semi-finals over Pakistan and New Zealand, respectively, they met in the final at Lord's with the West Indies defending their title from four years earlier with a 92-run victory.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-cricket-world-cup] West Indian batsman, Gordon Greenidge ended the tournament as the leading run scorer with 253 runs from four matches with English player Mike Hendrick ending up as the leading wicket-taker with ten wickets.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-cricket-world-cup] The eight teams at the tournament were split into two groups of four teams, with each team playing the others in their group in a single round-robin format.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-cricket-world-cup] The top two teams from each group then advance to the semi-finals to play in a single-elimination tournament.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-cricket-world-cup] The 1979 tournament saw the first qualifiers in a World Cup.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-cricket-world-cup] The 1979 ICC Trophy was held during late May and early June at various grounds in the English Midlands, with the two finalists qualifying for the World Cup where they joined the six Test nations who qualified automatically.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-cricket-world-cup] Sri Lanka and Canada qualified after defeating Denmark and Bermuda respectively in the semi-finals.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-cricket-world-cup] The opening round of matches took place on 9 June with four matches being played.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-cricket-world-cup] England took on Australia at Lord's and after the home team elected to field first, restricted the Australians to 97 for one with fine fielding and bowling.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-cricket-world-cup] After Andrew Hilditch dragged his second ball after lunch into the stumps, the Australians would be restricted for 159 which included four run-outs.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-cricket-world-cup] The run-chase saw Mike Brearley and Graham Gooch control the innings and led England to a six wicket victory.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-cricket-world-cup] In a very close semi-final match, England prevailed.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-cricket-world-cup] England began badly, falling to 38/2, before Mike Brearley (53 from 115 balls, 3 fours) and Graham Gooch (71 from 84 balls, 1 four, 3 sixes) resurrected the innings.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-cricket-world-cup] Derek Randall (42 from 50 balls, 1 four, 1 six) played well in the second half of the innings, as England recovered from 98/4 to post 221 (8 wickets, 60 overs).
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-cricket-world-cup] In the response, John Wright (69 from 137 balls) attacked well in the beginning.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-cricket-world-cup] However, the loss of wickets bogged New Zealand down, and despite several late flourishes in the batting order, New Zealand started to drop behind.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-cricket-world-cup] When New Zealand could not achieve the remaining 14 runs from the last over of the match, England went into the final.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-cricket-world-cup] Gordon Greenidge (73 from 107 balls, 5 fours, 1 six) and Desmond Haynes (65 from 115 balls, 4 fours) set a first wicket partnership of 132 runs in a match dominated by batting.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-cricket-world-cup] Vivian Richards and Clive Lloyd also contributed solidly, as West Indies ran up 293 (6 wickets, 60 overs) against Pakistan.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-cricket-world-cup] Majid Khan (81 from 124 balls, 7 fours) and Zaheer Abbas (93 from 122 balls) shared a second-wicket partnership of 166 runs in 36 overs in the response.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-cricket-world-cup] However, none of the other Pakistani batsmen flourished, with Javed Miandad being bowled for a duck first ball, and Pakistan lost 9/74, beginning with the dismissal of Abbas.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-cricket-world-cup] Pakistan was bowled out for 250 in 56.2 overs in the high-scoring semi-final, sending the West Indies to the final.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-cricket-world-cup] King especially savaged the English bowling, with a strike rate of 130.3.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-cricket-world-cup] The West Indies were 238/5 when the 139 run partnership ended with King’s dismissal.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-cricket-world-cup] But the openers, Mike Brearley (64 from 130 balls, 7 fours) and Geoff Boycott (57 from 105 balls, 3 fours) scored very slowly with a methodical opening partnership of 129 runs in 38 overs, playing as if the match were a five-day Test.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-cricket-world-cup] By the time both batsmen were out, the required run rate had risen too high, putting pressure on the later batsmen.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-cricket-world-cup] However, the loss of Derek Randall triggered a batting collapse in which England lost their last eight wickets for 11 runs to finish all out for 194 in 51 overs.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-cricket-world-cup] Gordon Greenidge ended the tournament as the leading run scorer with 253 runs coming from his four games.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-cricket-world-cup] Second was fellow West Indian player, Viv Richards who finished with 217 runs from four games which included the highest individual score of the tournament of 138 in the final.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-cricket-world-cup] Graham Gooch from England rounded out the top three.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-cricket-world-cup] Mike Hendrick from England was the leading wicket taker for the tournament with ten wickets from five matches with a three-way tie for second place with Brian McKechnie (New Zealand), Asif Iqbal (Pakistan) and Chris Old each taking nine wickets for the tournament.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-cricket-world-cup] The total attendance at the tournament was 132,000, including 25,000 at the final.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-icc-trophy] The **1979 ICC Trophy** was a limited overs cricket tournament held in England between 22 May and 21 June 1979.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-icc-trophy] It was the inaugural ICC Trophy tournament to be staged, with matches between the 15 participating teams played over 60 overs a team and with white clothing and red balls.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-icc-trophy] All matches were played in the Midlands.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-icc-trophy] The tournament served as the Cricket World Cup qualification process – the two finalists, Sri Lanka and Canada, qualified to take part in the 1979 World Cup.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-icc-trophy] The World Cup began on 9 June, just three days after Sri Lanka and Canada qualified for it by winning their ICC Trophy semi-finals.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-icc-trophy] The ICC Trophy final was held on 21 June at Worcestershire's ground at New Road, two days before the World Cup final.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-icc-trophy] Sri Lanka won the first ICC Trophy defeating Canada by 60 runs in the final.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-icc-trophy] East Africa who played in the first World Cup did not qualify this time, which meant there would be no nation from the African region participating in the 1979 World Cup.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-icc-trophy] The 15 teams were divided into three groups of five.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-icc-trophy] Each team played each other team in its group once in matches played between 22 May and 4 June, scoring four points for a win and two for a no-result (match started but not finished) or abandoned entirely without a ball being bowled.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-icc-trophy] The three group winners and the team with the fourth-highest points total after the group stage went forward to the semi-finals, the top team playing the fourth-ranked team and the team with the second-highest number of points playing the third.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-icc-trophy] Where teams finished with equal points totals, run rate was used to separate them.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-icc-trophy] The top five run scorers (total runs) are included in this table.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1979-icc-trophy] The top five wicket takers are listed in this table, listed by wickets taken and then by bowling average.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] The **1982 ICC Trophy** was a limited-overs cricket tournament held in England between 16 June and 10 July 1982.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] It was the second ICC Trophy tournament to be staged, with matches between the 16 participating teams played over 60 overs a team and with white clothing and red balls.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] As in the 1979 tournament, all matches were played in the Midlands, though on this occasion the final was held at Grace Road, Leicester.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] The tournament served as the Cricket World Cup qualification process – Zimbabwe, who didn't play in the first tournament, defeated Bermuda in the final to qualify for the 1983 World Cup.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] Bad weather hampered the tournament throughout, with many games called off early or abandoned entirely because of rain; West Africa suffered the most, seeing a result in only two of their seven group matches.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] Sri Lanka, who won the first tournament in 1979, had by now been promoted to Full Test and ODI status, and so did not take part, and automatically qualified for the World Cup.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] As a result only one spot was on offer to join the seven Full members in the World Cup which was won by Zimbabwe.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] The 16 teams were divided into two groups of eight.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] Each teams played each other team in its group once in matches played between 16 June and 5 July, scoring four points for a win and two for a no-result (match started but not finished) or abandoned entirely without a ball being bowled.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] The top two teams in each group went forward to the semi-finals, the top team (With the highest number of points) in one group playing the runner-up from the other group.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] Where teams finished with equal points totals, first the number of games won and secondly run rate was used to separate them.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] Kenya recorded an easy nine-wicket win over Gibraltar.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] The Europeans were dismissed for just 80 (RCR Patel 3-13) and their opponents rushed to victory in 14.2 overs, with Rehmann making 53 not out.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] In a low-scoring match, Papua New Guinea beat Hong Kong by four wickets.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] The young Dermot Reeve made 38 for Hong Kong and took 2-26, but the Papuans overhauled their target of 100 with 34.4 overs in hand.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] Elsewhere, Zimbabwe crushed the USA by 191 runs, thanks to a second-wicket partnership of 214 between David Houghton (135) and Kevin Curran (126 not out) that set them on their way to 332/4.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] The Americans were never remotely in the hunt, and 4-34 from Peter Rawson restricted their total to just 141.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] Gibraltar were in trouble at 42/4 against the United States, Shamshad Durrani having taken 3-12, before the rains came and put paid to any chance of a result.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] In a match reduced to 45 overs a team, Hong Kong's 207/7 (Andy Lorimer 53) was good enough, though Nissam Reuben's 6-2-7-3 was noteworthy, and the Israelis collapsed to 84 all out.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] In an all-African affair reduced to a 25-over game, Zimbabwe posted a highly competitive 192/4 (Houghton 71, Jack Heron 50) which Kenya never got anywhere near, making just 72/4 to lose by 120 runs.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] The game between Gibraltar and Zimbabwe saw no play at all, and nor did the matches between Kenya and the USA or between Canada and Hong Kong.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] The other game did produce a result, however, with Israel recovering from the depths of 32/5 to post a reasonable-looking 167/9, bolstered by 75 not out from Stanley Perlman.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] Despite losing an early wicket, however, the Papuans cantered to a nine-wicket win as Nigel Robert Agonia (86 not out) and Taunao Vai (75 not out) added an unbroken 157 for the second wicket.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] Israel were in dire straits at 74/6 against Kenya when the weather intervened, but that was the only action on this day, with Canada v Gibraltar and Papua New Guinea v the USA seeing not a ball bowled between them.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] Yet another rain-affected day saw no match reach a positive result.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] Canada had made 8/0 from nine overs against Zimbabwe when the players left the field, while Gibraltar reached 42/2 against Israel from ten.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] There was no play at all between Hong Kong and the United States.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] At last the weather held off for long enough to allow all three matches to reach a conclusion, albeit from a reduced number of overs.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] In a 55-over game, Papua New Guinea won against the odds by 30 runs against Canada, an unbeaten 101 from Vavine Pala guiding them to 231/7 from 83/6 while K Kalo took 4-26 as the Canadians could manage only 211 despite 50 from Tariq Javed.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] Gibraltar's 129/8 off 40 overs (Gordon Bacon 4-37) proved well short of what was required, as Des Greenwood and Reeve both made unbeaten scores of 56 to guide Hong Kong to an eight-wicket triumph.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] Finally, Israel slumped to 65 all out against Zimbabwe, with only Perlman reaching double figures and John Traicos taking 4-22.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] In reply the Africans scorched to a nine-wicket victory from a mere 7.3 overs, Houghton making 43.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] The North American derby produced a comprehensive 138-run win for Canada, who compiled 233 (Tariq Javed 68) before captain RJ Stevens took 4-26 as the USA could manage just 95 all out.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] Hong Kong dived to 47/7 before recovering to 105, but 39 not out from Hitesh Mehta saw Kenya home by three wickets.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] Finally, Papua New Guinea could manage only 94 in their game against Zimbabwe, and Houghton (44 not out) and Curran (30 not out) ensured a simple nine-wicket victory for the African team.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] An innings of 107 by IF Kirmani enabled Canada to make 242/8 against Kenya, and despite 53 from GA Musa 4-26 from Clement Neblett meant that the Africans fell 45 runs short.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] Gibraltar made a mere 55, the lowest total of the tournament, against Papua New Guinea with Pala taking 4-30, and the Papuans made short work of their target as they cruised to a nine-wicket win.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] Against the United States, Israel made a creditable 157, but NS Lashkari (76 not out) and Kamran Rasheed (65 not out) guided the Americans to a comfortable eight-wicket triumph.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] Canada won by a walk-over after Israel were unable to field a team due to a dispute between the players and management, but the teams decided to play a friendly match the following morning, which the Canadians won by three wickets.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] Elsewhere, 72 not out from Andy Lorimer contributed to a Hong Kong total of 192/4, which proved insufficient against Zimbabwe as their opponents won by seven wickets, future Test player Andy Pycroft hitting 83 not out and Heron 51.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] Kenya's total of 210/8 (Mehta 52) was too much for Papua New Guinea, for whom W Maha with 61 was the only man to pass 32; the Papuans were bowled out for 173 to lose by 37 runs.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] Despite having five men run out, Bangladesh compiled 246 (Gazi Ashraf 77) against West Africa, and this proved more than enough as their opponents fell to 96/7 before a late-innings rally from S Elliott (38) restored some respectability to leave them 76 runs short on 170/9.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] A hopelessly one-sided game saw Bermuda amass 348/9 against Malaysia, with Gladstone Brown (100) and Winston Reid (128) sharing an opening stand of 211.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] In reply, Banerji made a brave 34 but none of his team-mates reached double figures as the Malaysians were rolled over for just 64 to lose by 284 runs.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] Elvin James recorded astonishing bowling figures of 7.1-5-2-5 for Bermuda.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] And the Netherlands' 150/8 was sufficient to hold off East Africa (127) in a match that produced no fewer than 52 extras between the two teams.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] Rain destroyed any chance of meaningful play on this day.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] The matches between East Africa and Singapore and between the Netherlands and West Africa were abandoned without a ball being bowled, while the one game that did get underway saw Fiji reach 31/2 off 14 overs before a halt was called to proceedings.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] The match between the Netherlands and Singapore was abandoned with no play possible, but the other two games produced results.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] Bangladesh were restricted to 143 against East Africa thanks to William Bourne's 4-33, but no-one but Extras passed 20 in reply and Bangladesh won by 26 runs.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] Elsewhere, in a game reduced to a 20-over thrash, Bermuda's 153/5 (captain Colin Blades 45 not out) proved too much for Fiji, who could manage only 102/6 to lose by 51 runs.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] All three matches scheduled for this day - Bangladesh v Singapore, East Africa v Malaysia and Fiji v West Africa - were abandoned without a ball being bowled.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] The weather proved the only winner once more, as again all three games - Bangladesh v Fiji, Bermuda v the Netherlands and Singapore v West Africa - saw no play whatsoever.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] The most exciting of the four games scheduled for this day was a thrilling one-run victory in a 25-over match by Bangladesh over Malaysia.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] Raqibul Hasan made 35 in the Bangladeshi's 122/7, but Malaysia were closing on their target at 113/4 before two quick wickets fell; they ended just short on 121/6.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] Bermuda (116/4) beat Singapore (115) by six wickets thanks to 48 from Noel Gibbons after Winston Trott had claimed 4-27.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] Rain stopped play when Fiji were 79/2 in reply to the Netherlands' imposing 251/6, RJ Elferink hitting a fine 154 not out, but the Dutch had done enough to win on faster scoring rate.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] The East-West Africa clash was a disappointment, however, being called off after East Africa had reached 53/2 from 25.1 overs.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] Bangladesh had a game to forget against Bermuda, being bowled out for 67 with only Nazim Shirazi reaching double figures as Lionel Thomas took 4-13.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] The Bermudians lost three wickets in reply, but were never really in trouble as they reached their target from 15.5 overs.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] An opening stand of 94 between KW Arnold (54) and DC Patel (52) laid the foundations for East Africa's 220/7 against Fiji, and 4-21 from Desai made sure of an 88-run victory.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] Malaysia put up 128 in an all-south-east-Asian clash with Singapore, but their opponents glided to a six-wicket win with more than 15 overs to spate thanks to a knock of 67 from FJR Martens.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] Bangladesh (167/4) beat the Netherlands (163) by six wickets in a match that saw no outstanding individual performances, the highest score Yousuf Rahman's 45.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] Scores of 68 from Thomas and 51 from Allan Douglas helped Bermuda to 240 in a 56-over game, and despite 64 from DC Patel, East Africa could manage no more than 176, 64 runs adrift.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] Finally, there was no result in the game between Malaysia and West Africa, the Malaysians having made 219/9 from 58 overs (S Elliott 75, J Onyechi 57; K Kamalanathan 4-45) when the players were forced from the field.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] West Africa batted well against Bermuda to post a total of 249, with Elliott making 67 and Onyechi 53 despite Elvin James' 4-41.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] An unbroken partnership of 125 between Brown (78 not out) and Blades (82 not out) settled the matter, however, as the Bermudians won by seven wickets with more than 11 overs in hand.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] M Rajalingham took 5-39 for Singapore to restrict Fiji to 219, but it was not quite enough as the Singaporeans were bowled out 14 runs short for 205.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] Batting first, Bangladesh stuttered to 45/4, and a fifth-wicket stand of 52 was in vain as 4-31 from Kevin Curran restricted the team to an inadequate 124.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] David Houghton fell for 1 in the Zimbabwean reply, but once Heron (63 not out) and Curran (44) had added 103 for the second wicket there was only one winner, and they reached their target with more than 30 overs to spare to record an easy eight-wicket victory.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] Papua New Guinea were in all sorts of trouble after collapsing to 48/6, but Pala stopped the rot with 72 and they eventually reached 153 before being bowled out in 39 overs.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] Despite losing Brown before a run had been scored, Bermuda ran out six-wicket winners despite losing three wickets for four runs at one stage.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] Blades hit 69 not out in an unbeaten hundred partnership with John Tucker.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] Bangladesh put up a total of 224, thanks largely to an excellent 115 by Yousuf Rahman and 52 by Nazim Shirazi.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] From the commanding heights of 170/0, though, they lost all ten wickets for 54 runs (and their last six for 16) as La'a Aukopi returned outstanding figures of 5-14 from 11 overs.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] The Papuans were inspired by this to reach their target with three wickets and three overs remaining, W Maha hitting 60 in a three-wicket victory despite Bangladeshi captain and wicket-keeper Shafiq-ul-Haq making three stumpings in the innings.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] No batsman reached 50 in the Bermudian innings, but solid contributions from Brown (48), Blades (45) and Douglas (36) guided them to a reasonable 231/8 from their 60 overs.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] Duncan Fletcher was the pick of the Zimbabwean bowlers with 3-34 from nine overs.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1982-icc-trophy] Zimbabwe looked in a spot of bother at 30/2 with both openers gone, but the match and the Trophy were decided by half-centuries from Andy Pycroft, who made 82, and Craig Hodgson (57 not out); the Africans won with more than five overs to spare.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1987-cricket-world-cup-final] The **1987 Cricket World Cup Final** (known as the **Reliance Cricket World Cup Final** for sponsorship reasons) was a One Day International (ODI) cricket match played at Eden Gardens in Calcutta on 8 November 1987 to determine the winner of the 1987 Cricket World Cup.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1987-cricket-world-cup-final] It was contested by Australia and England, both of whom had yet to win the trophy.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1987-cricket-world-cup-final] The 1987 World Cup was the first World Cup to be hosted outside of England; it was also the first World Cup to feature a 50-over per side match format and the first time the final had been hosted at a venue other than Lord's.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1987-cricket-world-cup-final] It was estimated that between 70,000 and 90,000 spectators attended the match.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1987-cricket-world-cup-final] Australia went into the 1987 World Cup having lost a home Ashes series and their five previous ODI matches leading up to the tournament.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1987-cricket-world-cup-final] Steve Waugh, who was competing in his first World Cup and would become one of the players of the tournament, said that Australia were considered, both at home and abroad, to be "rank outsiders".
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1987-cricket-world-cup-final] Under coach Bob Simpson, the Australians undertook extra fielding sessions upon arriving in India, and an alcohol ban between games was also imposed.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1987-cricket-world-cup-final] While these somewhat revolutionary measures were ridiculed by other teams, Simpson's approach would pay off as Australia progressed through the tournament.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1987-cricket-world-cup-final] Placed in Group A along with India, New Zealand and Zimbabwe, the Australians finished second in the group behind India on run rate, which meant they would face Pakistan, who topped Group B, in the semi-final.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1987-cricket-world-cup-final] All these factors came to the fore when Australia upset the Pakistanis at the Gaddafi Stadium in Lahore; Batting first, Marsh and Boon put on 73 for the first wicket as the Australians finished with 267 for eight off their 50 overs, with Waugh scoring 18 runs off the final over.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1987-cricket-world-cup-final] In reply, Pakistan fell to 38 for three before Imran Khan and Javed Miandad set about resurrecting the innings.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1987-cricket-world-cup-final] But after they were removed, McDermott proceeded to clean up the tail and send Australia into its first World Cup final since 1975.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1987-cricket-world-cup-final] In Group B along with Pakistan, Sri Lanka and West Indies, England finished second behind Pakistan with wins over West Indies (considered the best cricket team in the world at the time) and Sri Lanka, and would face India in semi-final at the Wankhede Stadium in Bombay.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1987-cricket-world-cup-final] After being sent in by the home team, England posted 254 for six from its 50 overs, led by 115 from Graham Gooch (who ended the tournament as the leading run-scorer) and 56 from captain Mike Gatting.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1987-cricket-world-cup-final] India's innings started badly when home-town hero Sunil Gavaskar was bowled by Philip DeFreitas for 4.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1987-cricket-world-cup-final] The middle order, led by Mohammad Azharuddin, revived the home crowd's hopes, but after off-spinner Eddie Hemmings struck with four wickets, the chase collapsed, with the last five wickets falling for only 15 runs.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1987-cricket-world-cup-final] Like Australia, England had qualified for its second shot at glory, having previously lost to West Indies in 1979.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1987-cricket-world-cup-final] 8 November in Calcutta was a fine and hot day, but with less humidity than Bombay, where the England–India semi-final had been staged.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1987-cricket-world-cup-final] Preparation of the Eden Gardens wicket had been overseen by the renowned Adelaide Oval curator Les Burdett, who had been invited by the Bengal Cricket Association.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1987-cricket-world-cup-final] Allan Border won the toss and chose to bat.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1987-cricket-world-cup-final] As they had done for much of the tournament, openers Geoff Marsh and David Boon gave Australia a fantastic start, benefiting from the unusually wayward and undisciplined bowling of Philip DeFreitas and Gladstone Small (who conceded six no-balls) to post 52 off the first ten overs.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1987-cricket-world-cup-final] Waugh joined Veletta for the final over of the innings, to be bowled by DeFreitas.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1987-cricket-world-cup-final] The pair combined to score 11 runs off it to push Australia's score to 253, becoming the first team all tournament to score more than 250 against England.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1987-cricket-world-cup-final] The Australians took to the field with some confidence that their total was defendable; no team batting second at this World Cup had successfully chased 254.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1987-cricket-world-cup-final] England's innings started badly when McDermott trapped Tim Robinson in front for a golden duck midway through the first over.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1987-cricket-world-cup-final] Allan Lamb (45 from 55 balls, 4 fours) also posted a great innings, but it was in vain as the required run-rate for England began to rise.
[src:1987-cricket-world-cup-final/1987-cricket-world-cup-final] When England failed to score the last 17 runs from the final over, the cup went to Australia.
